But to weigh to ensure that we're all
kind of on the same playing field,

00:03:28.110 --> 00:03:32.370
let's just zoom back just a
little bit and talk about what

00:03:32.370 --> 00:03:34.970
it was that Apple tried to do.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:38.890
What is it that we accomplished
with QuickTime back in the day?

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:42.000
What was it that we set out
to do in the very beginning?

00:03:42.190 --> 00:03:44.960
Fundamentally,
we wanted to try to be the first

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:48.100
personal computer manufacturer
to put together audio and video,

00:03:48.130 --> 00:03:50.720
have them play synchronized
on a personal computer.

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:53.550
And we did that back as we were
doing research in the late 80s,

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:56.300
and we brought that out in the early,
like 1991.

00:03:56.300 --> 00:03:58.740
You guys remember some
of the codecs in here?

00:03:58.740 --> 00:03:59.540
Just an eye chart.

00:03:59.540 --> 00:04:00.910
You can't read this, but I can.

00:04:00.920 --> 00:04:03.220
Road Pizza, some of the old codecs.

00:04:03.220 --> 00:04:07.220
And year after year,
we steadily released new,

00:04:07.220 --> 00:04:11.550
big releases of QuickTime,
accelerating in the recent years to

00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:15.380
doing basically a major release a
year with a bunch of minor releases,

00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:18.740
but all with our eye toward a
couple of really important things.

00:04:18.740 --> 00:04:21.440
Quickly and aggressively
evolving the platform,

00:04:21.590 --> 00:04:25.310
maintaining backward compatibility
because we didn't want to lock

00:04:25.310 --> 00:04:28.630
people out of the content that
they'd created in QuickTime,

00:04:28.630 --> 00:04:29.240
ever.

00:04:29.240 --> 00:04:30.900
We still haven't done that.

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:34.580
With QuickTime,
one content still plays in QuickTime 6.3,

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:39.250
and we've held on to that as one of
the core components of what we do,

00:04:39.250 --> 00:04:42.060
and we'll do that for
the foreseeable future.

