And some of these go on to
sell millions of copies each,

00:08:16.390 --> 00:08:18.340
and every one of them installs QuickTime.

00:08:18.340 --> 00:08:21.560
And this is a very,
very interesting and very large business

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:23.400
that's run out of my group as well.

00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:26.130
So we get to watch that,
how it's growing and what the

00:08:26.130 --> 00:08:27.880
requests are for licensing.

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:29.500
Enhanced music CDs.

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:30.280
A lot of you guys have seen this.

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:32.010
A lot of you guys out here
likely have these discs,

00:08:32.080 --> 00:08:33.160
and you may not even know it.

00:08:33.220 --> 00:08:37.260
There's no kind of like unified
branding scheme about enhanced discs,

00:08:37.260 --> 00:08:39.420
but these are basically music CDs.

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:41.730
You put them in a dashboard of your car,
they play just fine.

00:08:41.990 --> 00:08:45.320
When you put them in a computer,
you get a full multimedia experience.

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:50.060
And that is traditionally and almost
exclusively delivered with QuickTime.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:54.940
And why do the music guys
use QuickTime exclusively?

00:08:55.300 --> 00:08:56.800
Because we're cross-platform.

00:08:56.800 --> 00:08:58.280
We talked about distribution earlier.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:00.310
Ninety-five percent of
all of our distribution.

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:01.170
Is on the PC.

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:03.920
But we've made sure that our
PC player looks and acts and

00:09:03.950 --> 00:09:05.610
feels just like the Mac player.

00:09:05.620 --> 00:09:07.470
We don't dumb down the codex.

00:09:07.630 --> 00:09:12.570
We don't make the experience like a lot
less interesting than on the Macintosh.

00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:15.120
And these music guys and the
other folks that are authoring

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:17.930
the content really respect that
and use QuickTime as a result.

00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:20.750
And some of these discs, as you know,
there's hundreds of them in

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:22.000
distribution at any time.

00:09:22.410 --> 00:09:25.520
Thousands of them have been done
since these things have started,

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:28.280
and some of them are done by
some incredibly large stars

00:09:28.460 --> 00:09:30.220
that sell millions of copies.

00:09:30.220 --> 00:09:31.670
copies.

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:32.790
And of course, digital cameras.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:34.300
This is pretty interesting.

00:09:34.300 --> 00:09:36.780
We started this just
about a year and a half,

00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:37.560
maybe two years ago.

00:09:37.560 --> 00:09:41.330
And now there's over 200 different
digital cameras from over 45

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:44.510
manufacturers around the world
who distribute QuickTime with

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:45.990
their digital cameras.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:47.720
You know,
this was the first year when more

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:50.810
digital cameras sold than film cameras,
and that'll never change.

00:09:50.870 --> 00:09:53.280
That will always stay that
way for the rest of time.

00:09:53.720 --> 00:09:56.340
You know, digital cameras have taken off,
and we're the only ones who

00:09:56.470 --> 00:09:57.520
are distributed this way.

00:09:57.520 --> 00:10:00.270
And what's even more interesting
is half of these cameras,

00:10:00.270 --> 00:10:03.530
100 of these cameras,
actually have a file format license.

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:05.520
We license them to QuickTime file format.

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:09.300
And in that file format,
they can capture, these still cameras

00:10:09.300 --> 00:10:12.840
capture short video clips,
and they record them right in the

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:15.230
QuickTime file format on the cameras.

00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:17.340
When you plug it into your
Mac or you plug it into your PC,

00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:18.630
you've got a QuickTime movie.

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:20.750
If you have QuickTime Pro,
you could trim the edges and you

00:10:20.750 --> 00:10:22.700
could combine a couple of them,
and then you could push

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:23.580
it up to a website.

00:10:23.720 --> 00:10:24.560
You could play it.

00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:25.320
It's just that easy.

00:10:25.540 --> 00:10:29.700
And so we continue to see a lot of
interest in the digital camera area,

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:32.470
you know, as we go forward.

00:10:32.930 --> 00:10:38.190
So, racing up from the beginning of time
to just the beginning of last year.

00:10:38.190 --> 00:10:42.240
Kind of like a where are things,
how are they going, distribution,

00:10:42.240 --> 00:10:44.800
support, how it's being used.

00:10:44.860 --> 00:10:46.880
But last year was actually,
for me certainly,

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:48.420
probably the most exciting year.

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:51.760
It was the year where Apple kind of put
its foot down on a set of architectural

00:10:52.370 --> 00:10:54.130
and technological directions.

00:10:54.140 --> 00:10:57.960
It was last year where we really
put a stake in the sand and said

00:10:58.030 --> 00:11:02.340
we are a company that's interested
in and building on standards.

00:11:02.360 --> 00:11:04.740
And it's not just
OS X or FireWire or USB,

00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:05.660
Bluetooth.

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:08.430
I mean, there's standards all
over the Macintosh now.

00:11:08.670 --> 00:11:11.100
Something you would never think of,
you know, 10 years ago,

00:11:11.100 --> 00:11:13.470
or even 5 years ago,
but now it's standards-based.

00:11:13.480 --> 00:11:15.000
QuickTime is no different.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.970
We've had lots of standards-based
codecs over the years,

00:11:18.150 --> 00:11:21.760
but now we've totally embraced
the industry standards of MPEG-4.

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:25.530
And with QuickTime 6 that
we launched last July,

00:11:25.530 --> 00:11:29.080
we really started down
this path in earnest.

00:11:29.130 --> 00:11:32.090
We jumped in with both feet like
no one else and built QuickTime.

00:11:32.410 --> 00:11:36.520
We built QuickTime 6 as an
ISO-compliant MPEG-4 architecture.

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:38.680
You know,
it's important to remember that when

00:11:38.680 --> 00:11:41.720
the International Organization for
Standards were deciding

00:11:41.720 --> 00:11:44.390
how to build MPEG-4,
the MPEG for the Internet.

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:48.420
MPEG-1 came out in the early '90s,
MPEG-2 in the mid-'90s,

00:11:48.420 --> 00:11:52.200
and very targeted applications,
very targeted data rates.

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:55.200
But what about an Internet-based MPEG?

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:58.200
And so they could have gone anywhere,
created one of their own.

00:11:58.250 --> 00:12:00.130
Well, they came to us,
and we worked with them.

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:02.190
And MPEG-4 file format ended up being
the most important thing for us.

00:12:02.360 --> 00:12:04.360
It's based on the QuickTime file format.

00:12:04.360 --> 00:12:06.360
We're incredibly proud of that.

00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:09.710
And, of course,
we deliver -- we were the first people

00:12:09.710 --> 00:12:14.320
to deliver a generally available,
widely distributed MPEG-4

00:12:14.540 --> 00:12:17.360
solution with MPEG-4 video,
AAC audio,

00:12:17.360 --> 00:12:20.820
support for the MP4 file extension,
which, you know,

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:22.360
kind of marks a file as MPEG-4.

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:25.370
And a bunch of other things
that do quality of streaming,

00:12:25.370 --> 00:12:28.050
instant on streaming,
the first people to do that,

00:12:28.120 --> 00:12:29.310
skip protection.

00:12:29.480 --> 00:12:31.230
And a host of other technologies
came with QuickTime 6.

00:12:31.390 --> 00:12:32.360
But again, we're proud of that.

00:12:32.360 --> 00:12:34.980
And again, the most important and the
most interesting part is our

00:12:34.980 --> 00:12:36.360
decision to go with standards.

00:12:36.360 --> 00:12:40.220
And what that meant was we now,
instead of standing by ourselves

00:12:40.220 --> 00:12:43.440
and just looking at real networks
and looking at Microsoft,

00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:46.910
who are looking back at us,
and battling it out based on, you know,

00:12:46.910 --> 00:12:49.780
a bunch of architectures,
trying to figure out -- you know,

00:12:49.780 --> 00:12:52.360
every once in a while,
we would all declare victory, right?

00:12:52.360 --> 00:12:55.280
Microsoft, real, Apple,
we'd all put out a press release.

00:12:55.380 --> 00:12:57.650
The most downloads,
the most subscriptions,

00:12:57.650 --> 00:12:59.360
the most Northwest in the U.S.

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:01.360
There's some kind of announcement.

00:13:01.360 --> 00:13:03.780
There's some kind of announcement that
we would all routinely make pounding

00:13:03.960 --> 00:13:05.350
our chests about what we were doing.

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:08.310
But while we were doing that,
there were some very definite losers.

00:13:08.360 --> 00:13:11.610
Content providers who were forced
to encode in multiple formats

00:13:11.790 --> 00:13:13.360
to reach the broadest audience.

00:13:13.360 --> 00:13:17.120
And end users who were forced to download
and install and use multiple players

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:19.360
to get the broadest range of content.

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:22.110
And you all know what happens
when you install two or,

00:13:22.180 --> 00:13:25.220
God forbid, three of these media
players on one computer.

00:13:25.360 --> 00:13:27.360
You know,
they don't exactly coexist peacefully.

00:13:27.360 --> 00:13:29.350
But this is typical
of a nascent industry.

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:30.360
This is typical of an industry
that's not really a media player.

00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:32.810
This is typical of an industry
that's just getting going and de

00:13:32.810 --> 00:13:35.350
facto standards battle it out.

00:13:35.390 --> 00:13:39.310
But like any other industry that matures,
the Internet itself,

00:13:39.370 --> 00:13:42.320
any other set of technologies
that have evolved,

00:13:42.380 --> 00:13:45.360
standards come in and provide
a level playing field.

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:47.630
Standards come in and
provide a set of repeatable,

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:51.500
dependable,
and reliable technologies that then the

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:56.350
industry can embrace and move forward
on and get rid of the various battles.

00:13:56.360 --> 00:13:59.240
And we believe MPEG-4 provides that.

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:04.060
A huge organization of
companies that support,

00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:05.360
use MPEG-4.

00:14:05.360 --> 00:14:08.490
And what I'd like to do
now is invite Rob Conan,

00:14:08.490 --> 00:14:11.360
who is the president of the M4IF,
the MPEG-4 Industry Forum,

00:14:11.430 --> 00:14:14.410
to come up here and talk for a couple
minutes about what's going on in the

00:14:14.510 --> 00:14:16.310
world of MPEG-4 and where it's all going.

00:14:16.770 --> 00:14:17.360
Welcome.

