of open standards,
and MPEG-4 is one of the promising open

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:30.700
standards that we have around today.

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:33.590
Yesterday,
I got an email from a very small company.

00:14:33.590 --> 00:14:35.680
I'd never heard of them from Norway.

00:14:35.790 --> 00:14:36.690
They're called Visiware.

00:14:36.710 --> 00:14:39.700
And they said, "Well,
we have this new cool MPEG-4 product.

00:14:39.700 --> 00:14:44.170
It's a mobile video conferencing
system." It has a little tiny camera

00:14:44.230 --> 00:14:46.700
and a tiny screen in front of your eyes.

00:14:46.750 --> 00:14:48.700
You're wireless,
and you can do video conferencing.

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:50.700
It's mobile, and it's using MPEG-4.

00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:53.060
There was another announcement today.

00:14:53.060 --> 00:14:54.600
It was made by Microsoft.

00:14:54.600 --> 00:14:56.640
Am I allowed to say that word here?

00:14:56.750 --> 00:14:57.700
And JVC.

00:14:57.700 --> 00:15:01.610
And they have a new mobile device out,
and it supports MPEG-4.

00:15:01.700 --> 00:15:05.770
This illustrates that small
companies and large companies alike

00:15:05.770 --> 00:15:09.600
have to support open standards,
whether they want to or not,

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:12.700
because it makes sense and because
it makes the consumer happy.

00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:15.900
The MPEG-4 Industry Forum,
which I represent here and I'm

00:15:15.900 --> 00:15:19.700
proud to represent here today,
is a forum of about 100 companies

00:15:19.700 --> 00:15:24.670
that all create MPEG-4 technology
in various different industries.

00:15:24.700 --> 00:15:28.690
And I will say a little bit about
all the different industries.

00:15:28.710 --> 00:15:32.260
And they all believe in the value
of open standards to create an

00:15:32.290 --> 00:15:37.510
interoperable multimedia ecosystem where
you have the same content representation

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:38.700
working across all your devices.

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:42.690
So you can move content from
your mobile phone to your PC.

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:47.140
and to your DVD player and it just works.

00:15:47.610 --> 00:15:50.300
Of course,
this starts with QuickTime 6 today,

00:15:50.330 --> 00:15:54.200
which supports MPEG-4 video,
MPEG-4 audio, advanced audio coding,

00:15:54.200 --> 00:15:55.690
the MPEG-4 file format.

00:15:55.710 --> 00:15:58.850
We see support for MPEG-4 in phones.

00:15:58.850 --> 00:16:04.370
The 3G and the 2.5G phones in the world,
around the world, wherever you go,

00:16:04.370 --> 00:16:05.860
support MPEG-4.

00:16:05.860 --> 00:16:07.070
We see it in PDAs.

00:16:07.070 --> 00:16:11.360
Sony has this really cool Clia PDA,
which supports MPEG-4,

00:16:11.360 --> 00:16:17.220
and they've announced their
PS Portable to be released next year,

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:18.460
which also does MPEG-4.

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:19.980
We see it in DVD players.

00:16:20.050 --> 00:16:23.970
Some of them use the brand name Devix,
which you may have heard.

00:16:23.970 --> 00:16:26.760
Devix is just an MPEG-4
compliant implementation.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:30.840
We, of course, see the iPods and iTunes,
which use MPEG-4 audio.

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:33.260
We see video cameras
that do digital video,

00:16:33.260 --> 00:16:36.300
but also do MPEG-4 if you want
to post stuff to... ...the web.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:39.860
And we see a host of internet
players that all support MPEG-4.

00:16:39.860 --> 00:16:45.400
You can get MPEG-4 plugins also for
Windows Media and also for real.

00:16:48.130 --> 00:16:52.450
So it looks like our original
vision of MPEG-4 as something that

00:16:52.520 --> 00:16:58.300
works across industries and across
networks and devices is coming true.

00:16:59.170 --> 00:17:02.100
And the industry
projections are interesting.

00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:06.510
They all say, initially there will be
competition with Microsoft,

00:17:06.510 --> 00:17:13.000
but in the long run the market will
understand the value of an open standard,

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:14.470
and they will choose the open standard.

00:17:16.570 --> 00:17:20.380
And also because the open
standard has been created by

00:17:20.380 --> 00:17:22.640
people from all these areas,
and they understand the

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:24.630
needs from all these areas,
from the mobile industry,

00:17:24.730 --> 00:17:28.270
from the CE industry,
and from the computer industry.

00:17:29.070 --> 00:17:30.990
So let's take a look at
where we are tomorrow,

00:17:31.020 --> 00:17:31.710
where we will be.

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:33.860
There's a new MPEG-4
video coder coming up.

00:17:33.990 --> 00:17:35.660
It's called Advanced Video Coding.

00:17:35.660 --> 00:17:40.060
The experts in the industry already
say it's the best video codec around.

00:17:40.120 --> 00:17:43.740
It beats all of the other
proprietary and standard formats.

00:17:43.740 --> 00:17:46.970
Advanced Audio Coding,
supported in your iPod

00:17:47.060 --> 00:17:51.190
today and in your iTunes,
is already the best audio codec.

00:17:51.250 --> 00:17:53.510
And with high-efficiency AAC,
as it's called,

00:17:53.550 --> 00:17:56.960
you can get CD-quality stereo
audio in 48 kilobits per second.

00:17:57.580 --> 00:18:00.620
And that's already being used
in like Digital Radio Mondial,

00:18:00.620 --> 00:18:03.140
which is a satellite-based radio system,
or XM,

00:18:03.140 --> 00:18:05.240
which is also satellite-based radio.

00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:12.150
And we will see, with AVC,
Advanced Video Coding, and with AAC,

00:18:12.160 --> 00:18:15.480
Advanced Audio Coding,
we will see MPEG-4 being adopted

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:19.970
in the broadcast industry,
in the packaged media like the DVD,

00:18:20.220 --> 00:18:24.940
in the mobile entertainment industry,
in lots of great and funny devices,

00:18:24.940 --> 00:18:28.520
and of course, and finally,
on the internet.

00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:31.130
And that brings me back
to QuickTime and to Frank,

00:18:31.130 --> 00:18:34.000
and I want to thank you for
allowing me to say a few words,

00:18:34.110 --> 00:18:34.640
Frank.

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:35.620
Thanks, Rob.

00:18:35.710 --> 00:18:36.680
Appreciate it.

00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:43.690
Rob mentioned a couple of
things that are important.

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:48.370
Because of the standard,
we want as many people as possible

00:18:48.570 --> 00:18:49.820
to embrace and use the standard.

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:53.830
We look at Windows Media,
and the guys at Microsoft have

00:18:53.910 --> 00:18:56.750
done an incredible job with the
video codec and the audio codec.

00:18:57.240 --> 00:18:59.630
Unfortunately, it's closed,
and it's proprietary,

00:18:59.640 --> 00:19:01.130
and it's only Microsoft's.

00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:03.180
Real Networks has dabbled in standards.

00:19:03.180 --> 00:19:06.630
Real Networks has a plug-in for
their player that supports MPEG-4,

00:19:06.630 --> 00:19:07.650
which is a great start.

00:19:07.870 --> 00:19:11.370
And we would invite them,
and I routinely invite Microsoft,

00:19:11.370 --> 00:19:15.310
to join us and support MPEG-4,
because with the inclusion of

00:19:15.310 --> 00:19:18.100
MPEG in all of their players,
it just only gets better.

00:19:18.180 --> 00:19:20.720
So, I mean,
it's a good point Rob brought out.

00:19:20.850 --> 00:19:22.610
He's totally platform agnostic.

00:19:22.610 --> 00:19:25.180
I tend to forget about
that every once in a while,

00:19:25.180 --> 00:19:27.180
and kind of stick to QuickTime.

00:19:27.590 --> 00:19:29.980
The last thing we did,
the most recent thing we did,

00:19:30.020 --> 00:19:32.010
was probably one of the most
exciting things that I had done

00:19:32.010 --> 00:19:36.280
with QuickTime since I took
this job a number of years ago,

00:19:36.550 --> 00:19:40.730
is watching us be able to cash
in on some of the dividends

00:19:41.160 --> 00:19:42.340
from our investment standards.

00:19:42.340 --> 00:19:46.110
I mean, just, not even a year ago,
we started shipping, you know,

00:19:46.220 --> 00:19:48.490
QuickTime 6 with our MPEG-4 support.

00:19:48.500 --> 00:19:52.310
And now, with QuickTime 6.3,
we're delivering the

00:19:52.340 --> 00:19:56.080
next logical extension,
the whole new industry's

00:19:56.080 --> 00:20:00.320
worth of support for 3GPP,
Third Generation Partnership Project.

00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:04.040
This is a group of companies.

00:20:04.240 --> 00:20:09.760
There's actually 434 companies that
are members of the 3GPP organization.

00:20:09.760 --> 00:20:15.980
And they, like the M4AF organization,
are dedicated to the use of,

00:20:15.990 --> 00:20:18.600
the support of,
and the management of a standard,

00:20:18.940 --> 00:20:23.340
but for, not so much for the internet,
as much as for wireless devices,

00:20:23.340 --> 00:20:26.320
cell phones,
3G cell phones to be specific.

00:20:26.330 --> 00:20:30.180
This support of QuickTime 6.3
introduced a couple of new,

00:20:30.340 --> 00:20:33.300
one new codec,
a couple of new file formats,

00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:39.320
basically AAC and AMR audio,
MPEG-4 video in H.263,

00:20:39.320 --> 00:20:40.320
but as a .3GP file.

00:20:40.320 --> 00:20:42.300
A new file extension.

00:20:42.360 --> 00:20:44.320
So, we're going to talk about that.

00:20:44.320 --> 00:20:46.320
And then, we're going to talk about
the extension to QuickTime,

00:20:46.320 --> 00:20:46.320
and one that's incredibly
important for this,

00:20:46.320 --> 00:20:46.320
the mobile world.

00:20:46.320 --> 00:20:50.320
And including 3G text,
support for the 3G file format.

00:20:50.460 --> 00:20:52.190
We can play back .AMR files.

00:20:52.670 --> 00:20:56.260
And, if you guys have ever seen any of
these absolutely incredible phones,

00:20:56.390 --> 00:20:58.320
this one's from NTT DoCoMo.

00:20:58.320 --> 00:21:00.320
It has two cameras built into it.

00:21:00.320 --> 00:21:02.280
I mean, I'm looking at you guys now.

00:21:02.360 --> 00:21:04.290
I'm going to take a picture of you guys.

00:21:04.360 --> 00:21:06.320
I just took a picture.

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:08.320
This is the screen.

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:10.210
I mean, it's absolutely incredible.

00:21:10.600 --> 00:21:11.270
Unfortunately, it doesn't work here.

00:21:11.320 --> 00:21:11.640
The camera does.

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:12.300
But nothing else really turns on.

00:21:12.400 --> 00:21:16.300
But when you land at Narita
and you turn this phone on,

00:21:16.360 --> 00:21:17.300
it takes on a whole new meaning.

00:21:17.300 --> 00:21:19.280
This thing is just incredible,
what it can do.

00:21:19.340 --> 00:21:23.300
And in the back,
they have these SD cards.

00:21:23.300 --> 00:21:26.300
And the SDV format is
what these cards read.

00:21:26.300 --> 00:21:28.280
And we support those as well.

00:21:28.380 --> 00:21:30.300
And we're really excited about this.

00:21:30.300 --> 00:21:34.300
We were in Tokyo just two
weeks ago doing the 6.3 launch.

00:21:34.300 --> 00:21:38.300
And we had 80 members of the
press show up to our launch.

00:21:38.300 --> 00:21:42.280
A gentleman, Natsuno-san,
who is the founder of the NTT DoCoMo,

00:21:42.280 --> 00:21:44.280
is the founder of iMode.

00:21:44.280 --> 00:21:46.280
If you know anything about
what's going on over in Japan,

00:21:46.280 --> 00:21:50.270
iMode is an incredible service provided
by NTT DoCoMo to provide access

00:21:50.270 --> 00:21:52.280
to information and entertainment.

00:21:52.280 --> 00:21:54.280
And they've extended that now to iMotion.

00:21:54.340 --> 00:21:56.280
Well, Natsuno-san came to our launch.

00:21:56.280 --> 00:21:56.280
He spoke on behalf.

00:21:56.280 --> 00:21:58.280
This guy's a rock star over in Japan.

00:21:58.280 --> 00:22:00.240
He gets like Steve Jobs treatment
when he's there.

00:22:00.270 --> 00:22:01.280
It was wild.

00:22:01.280 --> 00:22:05.280
And he spoke at our conference,
and it was just incredibly well received.

00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:10.280
Because we took prototype versions
of QuickTime 6.3 months ago,

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:12.240
back like December or something.

00:22:12.260 --> 00:22:14.260
And we gave them to a number of folks,
including DoCoMo,

00:22:14.260 --> 00:22:17.760
who immediately started building out
their iMotion content service with all

00:22:17.870 --> 00:22:22.260
of their thousands of content providers
creating content using QuickTime 6.3.

00:22:22.260 --> 00:22:25.260
And when the service launched,
they had all the content they needed.

00:22:25.260 --> 00:22:28.260
And it just worked based on QuickTime.

00:22:28.310 --> 00:22:30.250
The way this works,
there's a couple different ways.

00:22:30.260 --> 00:22:34.370
First is professional
content providers with,

00:22:34.390 --> 00:22:37.080
you know,
Macs or PCs with QuickTime-based

00:22:37.080 --> 00:22:39.260
tools capture their content,
get it somehow,

00:22:39.260 --> 00:22:42.240
and simply encode as a 3G file.

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:44.240
I'll show you that in a little bit.

00:22:44.240 --> 00:22:46.240
Push it out to one of these
mobile service providers,

00:22:46.240 --> 00:22:49.020
to their basic cell towers,
and then people with these cell

00:22:49.020 --> 00:22:52.240
phones can just surf around and
find the content and play it back,

00:22:52.240 --> 00:22:53.210
save it or whatever.

00:22:53.240 --> 00:22:57.050
Equally as important and interesting
is what you can do as a consumer.

00:22:57.240 --> 00:22:59.240
You know,
instead of taking a snapshot of you guys,

00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:02.240
I could have captured 15 or
30 seconds worth of video,

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:06.240
and then simply go to the address book,
dial up another cell phone,

00:23:06.240 --> 00:23:10.240
and email the movie to you,
or dial up an email address

00:23:10.240 --> 00:23:12.220
and send it to a desktop.

00:23:12.220 --> 00:23:14.640
So this is where QuickTime, you know,
QuickTime's role is

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:15.220
important to point out.

00:23:15.550 --> 00:23:17.220
QuickTime is not on these phones.

00:23:17.220 --> 00:23:19.210
This is the beauty of
working with the standard.

00:23:19.220 --> 00:23:22.870
We don't have to port--shut this
off so I don't have to look at

00:23:22.890 --> 00:23:27.220
myself-- we don't have to port
QuickTime to every device that wants

00:23:27.220 --> 00:23:30.000
to be a member of this 3G community.

00:23:30.350 --> 00:23:31.220
That's the beauty of standards.

00:23:31.220 --> 00:23:34.070
We do what we do best,
content creation and playback.

00:23:34.220 --> 00:23:38.110
We're not a 3G company,
but we get to play in the 3G industry.

00:23:38.220 --> 00:23:42.200
So content creation is what we do best,
and we continue to do that.

00:23:42.200 --> 00:23:45.190
And playback on a desktop
is what we do best,

00:23:45.190 --> 00:23:46.200
and we continue to do that.

00:23:46.200 --> 00:23:49.200
And the standards industry takes
care of everything in between,

00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:53.200
from the servers to the cell phones
and all the various technologies

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:54.170
required to play in this space.

00:23:54.210 --> 00:23:56.190
There's lots of other phones, too.

00:23:56.200 --> 00:23:59.200
This is the 3650 from Nokia that
actually does a beautiful job,

00:23:59.200 --> 00:24:02.170
and you can actually take pictures
and short videos here and use them.

00:24:02.200 --> 00:24:06.160
The set of services aren't available
yet like the Japanese have.

00:24:06.260 --> 00:24:08.200
It's very much like stepping into
the future when you go there,

00:24:08.200 --> 00:24:12.070
and very depressing to step back
into the past when you come back.

00:24:12.310 --> 00:24:15.180
It's really amazing if you
ever get a chance to try it.

00:24:15.180 --> 00:24:17.180
And there's a whole bunch of companies.

00:24:17.180 --> 00:24:20.390
This doesn't even begin to touch
the types of companies that are

00:24:20.390 --> 00:24:24.120
investing in the evolution and
development of the 3G industry.

00:24:24.180 --> 00:24:25.160
It's vast.

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:27.180
It's really kind of
Japanese-centric right now,

00:24:27.180 --> 00:24:30.260
moving out to the Pacific Rim,
to Europe and the U.S., and

00:24:30.570 --> 00:24:33.180
hopefully not too distant future,
within the next couple of years.

00:24:33.180 --> 00:24:36.180
We're meeting with all the
companies that are involved in this,

00:24:36.280 --> 00:24:39.180
all the big infrastructure manufacturers,
all the content providers,

00:24:39.180 --> 00:24:42.900
all the handset manufacturers,
to make sure that the standard

00:24:42.900 --> 00:24:45.160
and that QuickTime 6.3 and the
things that we're doing together

00:24:45.160 --> 00:24:49.160
and the tools that you guys create
can all work to create content.

00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:53.160
And to talk just a little bit
more about the world of 3G,

00:24:53.160 --> 00:24:57.160
I'd like to invite Roberto Castagna
from Nokia to come up here

00:24:57.160 --> 00:24:58.160
and talk a little bit.

00:24:58.200 --> 00:25:01.000
Roberto's a long-time
friend and colleague,

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:04.160
member of the standards community,
to talk a little bit about the 3G world.

00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:05.160
Roberto, thank you.

00:25:05.160 --> 00:25:06.950
Welcome.

00:25:09.630 --> 00:25:10.090
Thank you.

00:25:10.090 --> 00:25:11.500
Good morning, everybody.

00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:15.450
Yeah, actually I have two messages that
I would like to deliver to you today.

00:25:15.550 --> 00:25:17.640
One message is a little
bit about the past,

00:25:17.840 --> 00:25:20.500
and the other message is
more about the future.

00:25:20.500 --> 00:25:23.770
And the message about the
past is actually a little

00:25:23.900 --> 00:25:27.500
bit where do we come from,
and what did we do together with Apple,

00:25:27.570 --> 00:25:30.500
especially with the
QuickTime team at Apple.

00:25:30.500 --> 00:25:33.500
And of course,
Nokia being a telecom company,

00:25:33.500 --> 00:25:35.500
we have been always
working with standards,

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:37.970
because that's the only way
that you can have the devices

00:25:38.040 --> 00:25:39.500
interoperate with each other.

00:25:39.500 --> 00:25:42.500
And Nokia is involved in
several standardization bodies,

00:25:42.500 --> 00:25:45.500
but of course the 3GPP is now
the standardization body for us.

00:25:45.500 --> 00:25:49.180
So that's where we are really
creating the foundations for the

00:25:49.180 --> 00:25:53.500
2.5G and 3G telecommunications.

00:25:53.500 --> 00:25:58.610
And it was a couple of years ago
that we were starting to now address,

00:25:58.610 --> 00:26:01.600
in addition to the very
simple application,

00:26:01.620 --> 00:26:04.500
which is voice,
we started to address other applications.

00:26:04.500 --> 00:26:07.610
We started to address other multimedia
applications on mobile terminals,

00:26:07.760 --> 00:26:10.950
namely the multimedia messaging,
which is what allows you to

00:26:11.010 --> 00:26:14.500
create content on your terminal
and send it to other terminals,

00:26:14.500 --> 00:26:18.330
and of course also mobile streaming.

00:26:18.540 --> 00:26:22.500
And it was pretty clear that the 3GPP
needed to address this discussion,

00:26:22.500 --> 00:26:26.500
and I think we did a fantastic
investment a couple of years ago.

00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:33.500
I have been working with Dave Singer in
the MPEG team for several years,

00:26:33.500 --> 00:26:36.490
and he said,
"Why don't you come to the 3GPP?"

00:26:36.500 --> 00:26:40.500
And that was probably one of the
best things that I did in that group,

00:26:40.700 --> 00:26:45.140
because it really helped us bring
together the culture of the open

00:26:45.140 --> 00:26:50.530
standard multimedia that Apple has
had in the PC world for several

00:26:50.950 --> 00:26:54.500
years into the 3GPP community.

00:26:54.710 --> 00:27:02.490
And together with the help of
Dave and other companies there,

00:27:02.600 --> 00:27:05.550
we have developed a multimedia
architecture which is entirely

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:07.440
based on open standards.

00:27:07.570 --> 00:27:10.820
We have transport protocols,
we have media formats, we have everything

00:27:10.820 --> 00:27:12.500
based on open standards.

00:27:12.500 --> 00:27:15.500
And of course we have a 3GPP file format.

00:27:15.500 --> 00:27:21.500
And it has been really great that very
soon after the standard was finalized,

00:27:21.500 --> 00:27:26.500
then Apple released QuickTime 6.3 that
actually supports these 3GPP formats.

00:27:26.540 --> 00:27:31.500
Today we have a situation in which you
can really create content across devices.

00:27:31.500 --> 00:27:34.410
You can create content on mobile phones,
you can create content

00:27:34.470 --> 00:27:37.290
on personal computers,
and this content can travel

00:27:37.340 --> 00:27:39.490
across a variety of networks.

00:27:39.500 --> 00:27:40.400
It's really exciting.

00:27:40.540 --> 00:27:44.500
You will see demos today and
also later during the conference.

00:27:44.510 --> 00:27:47.500
You can actually create
content on GSM phones,

00:27:47.500 --> 00:27:52.500
transfer to your PC, put titles,
do some editing,

00:27:52.550 --> 00:27:55.500
and then you can send them
via email to a phone in Japan,

00:27:55.500 --> 00:27:56.500
and then it still works.

00:27:56.500 --> 00:27:58.380
And all of this is
based on open standards.

00:27:58.500 --> 00:28:00.500
This is really great.

00:28:00.640 --> 00:28:05.020
And in addition to that,
we also have evidence that even industry

00:28:05.100 --> 00:28:09.500
players that were actually working on
proprietary formats are now actually

00:28:09.500 --> 00:28:12.500
being pulled towards open standards.

00:28:12.520 --> 00:28:14.500
Since Frank named it,
now I feel allowed to name it myself,

00:28:14.500 --> 00:28:19.510
but also real networks actually is now
providing support for 3GPP formats on

00:28:19.610 --> 00:28:21.500
the mobile version of their player.

00:28:21.500 --> 00:28:24.350
And this is really exciting
because it really means exactly

00:28:24.710 --> 00:28:29.500
what Rob was saying earlier,
that when open standards start to work,

00:28:29.710 --> 00:28:32.170
then the whole industry is
clearly attracted because

00:28:32.170 --> 00:28:34.500
it's a win-win situation.

00:28:34.500 --> 00:28:35.500
So this is really great.

00:28:35.620 --> 00:28:39.500
And actually,
as a thank you to Apple for their work,

00:28:39.500 --> 00:28:42.700
actually I have here a recyclable
wooden mobile phone that

00:28:42.810 --> 00:28:46.040
I will leave here for Frank,
just to remind you about the

00:28:46.040 --> 00:28:47.500
beauty of open standards.

00:28:47.500 --> 00:28:49.630
And then when you get
tired of open standards,

00:28:49.630 --> 00:28:53.500
you can also use it to open bottles,
which is maybe more interesting.

00:28:53.500 --> 00:28:55.300
So it's here.

00:28:55.690 --> 00:28:58.500
But this was the message about the past.

00:28:58.500 --> 00:29:00.500
Now the message about the future.

00:29:00.500 --> 00:29:04.500
And this is very much about your,
and maybe my being, developers.

00:29:04.500 --> 00:29:06.500
This is a developer conference.

00:29:06.730 --> 00:29:11.190
And typically, let's say until today,
the idea of developers has always

00:29:11.190 --> 00:29:13.500
been a sort of vertical idea.

00:29:13.500 --> 00:29:16.500
We are here today in the
Apple Developers Conference.

00:29:16.500 --> 00:29:18.440
Of course, we have Nokia developers.

00:29:18.500 --> 00:29:20.490
We have Series 60.

00:29:20.500 --> 00:29:24.440
Series 60 is the software platform
that Nokia is also licensing

00:29:24.550 --> 00:29:26.500
for mobile phone manufacturers.

00:29:26.500 --> 00:29:27.490
And we have Series 60 developers.

00:29:27.500 --> 00:29:30.450
The idea of developers
were always vertical.

00:29:30.500 --> 00:29:34.500
But now,
especially for the mobile environment,

00:29:34.500 --> 00:29:37.500
now that we have this fantastic
platform of open standards,

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:41.500
which already guarantees interoperability
across devices and across networks,

00:29:41.500 --> 00:29:46.480
the exciting message today is that
the concept of developer community

00:29:46.500 --> 00:29:48.500
is not anymore a vertical one.

00:29:48.770 --> 00:29:51.700
Today, the developers of Apple and
the developers of Nokia and the

00:29:51.700 --> 00:29:54.500
developers of Sony Ericsson and
the developers of Series 60,

00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:58.930
they're actually creating one single,
big developer community which can

00:29:58.990 --> 00:30:02.500
leverage this open standard platform.

00:30:02.500 --> 00:30:06.500
And this is a clear case in which
the total is bigger than simply

00:30:06.500 --> 00:30:08.330
the sum of the different parts.

00:30:08.500 --> 00:30:10.500
And I think this is really great.

00:30:10.510 --> 00:30:13.500
I'm extremely excited
about being part of that.

00:30:13.500 --> 00:30:17.500
And I really encourage you to, let's say,
to think different.

00:30:17.500 --> 00:30:18.500
I've seen it on a couple of T-shirts.

00:30:18.500 --> 00:30:19.470
And really do that.

00:30:19.500 --> 00:30:25.500
And you have a golden opportunity to
expand the scope of your activity.

00:30:25.630 --> 00:30:29.500
As developers to the mobile world,
you have the opportunity of bridging,

00:30:29.500 --> 00:30:33.470
creating the famous bridge between
the Internet and the mobile world.

00:30:33.500 --> 00:30:38.480
So I think this is a good day.

00:30:38.500 --> 00:30:40.500
I think it's great that
there is this opportunity.

00:30:40.500 --> 00:30:44.090
And I strongly encourage you to
take advantage of that in your

00:30:44.090 --> 00:30:45.500
work and in your future activity.

00:30:45.500 --> 00:30:47.500
Good luck and thanks a lot.

00:30:52.700 --> 00:30:53.700
Thanks, Roberto.

00:30:53.700 --> 00:30:54.700
Appreciate it.

00:30:54.700 --> 00:31:01.080
Roberto, I think this is the phone you
should have put the real player on.

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:11.960
I'll show you in the visualizer later.

00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:11.970
It's wood.

00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:11.970
Sorry, I can't help myself.

00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:11.970
So, I'm

00:31:13.490 --> 00:31:16.640
Last couple of things
I wanted to talk about.

00:31:16.640 --> 00:31:21.330
As we evolve QuickTime,
as we move forward, the sea of APIs,

00:31:21.420 --> 00:31:27.600
2,400 some odd APIs that make up
the QuickTime library of routines

00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:28.890
and things that you can play with.

00:31:29.140 --> 00:31:31.650
One thing we haven't done,
we haven't really radically changed

00:31:31.650 --> 00:31:36.300
the way that you can get access to the
codecs that we build into QuickTime.

00:31:36.300 --> 00:31:38.010
We've had a lot of people ask us, "Well,
this is great.

00:31:38.010 --> 00:31:39.360
You're supporting these new formats.

00:31:39.360 --> 00:31:40.970
You're supporting these new technologies.

00:31:40.970 --> 00:31:42.360
You're supporting all this new stuff.

00:31:42.560 --> 00:31:43.450
How do we get access?

00:31:43.450 --> 00:31:46.820
Do we have to write new tools,
new applications?" No.

00:31:46.820 --> 00:31:51.290
Almost every time,
the same applications that you

00:31:51.360 --> 00:31:56.170
use before QuickTime 6.3 came out,
one day you're editing your

00:31:56.170 --> 00:31:59.320
DV file and Final Cut or some other
application and you export it and

00:31:59.400 --> 00:32:01.630
you can save it as an MPEG-4 file.

00:32:01.630 --> 00:32:06.520
You install QuickTime 6.3 and
the 3GPP codecs just show up.

00:32:06.620 --> 00:32:09.430
And what I wanted to
demonstrate--I'll collect all my toys.

00:32:09.430 --> 00:32:11.740
Tim, I'll leave the clicker right here.

00:32:11.750 --> 00:32:19.730
What I wanted to demonstrate
was making a long walk,

00:32:19.830 --> 00:32:22.190
a very long walk.

00:32:24.630 --> 00:32:27.180
What I wanted to demonstrate
to you guys is how this looks.

00:32:27.180 --> 00:32:32.050
Here's Final Cut Pro,
and we have a project in here.

00:32:32.050 --> 00:32:33.890
This is Red Hot Chili Peppers.

00:32:33.890 --> 00:32:36.400
This DV file is a short little clip.

00:32:36.480 --> 00:32:38.870
Remember,
the 3G world is not a long format world.

00:32:38.930 --> 00:32:41.700
You don't really watch
hour-long content on your phone.

00:32:41.700 --> 00:32:45.110
There's certain battery
issues that come into play.

00:32:45.110 --> 00:32:46.890
But it's short form.

00:32:46.900 --> 00:32:49.150
As I sat there in the airport,
I'm downloading little

00:32:49.150 --> 00:32:50.540
movie clips and audio clips.

00:32:50.540 --> 00:32:52.230
And this is a good example of one.

00:32:52.240 --> 00:32:54.480
This file, this DV file is 193 megabytes.

00:32:54.500 --> 00:32:57.770
And I'm going to play it,
and you can get a sense for what

00:32:57.820 --> 00:32:59.890
it looks like on the computer.

00:33:13.700 --> 00:33:16.480
That's like a classic little
clip that you would get on

00:33:16.480 --> 00:33:18.240
one of the iMotion service.

00:33:18.250 --> 00:33:21.240
I mean, I found tons of this kind of
stuff in Japan when I was there.

00:33:21.280 --> 00:33:23.170
But now the question is, what do you do?

00:33:23.170 --> 00:33:26.470
How do you go from almost 200
megabytes to something that will

00:33:26.470 --> 00:33:29.680
fit on a cell phone over the
wireless internet that they have?

00:33:29.740 --> 00:33:34.220
Well, with installing QuickTime 6.3,
we just go to Export,

00:33:34.220 --> 00:33:38.300
Using QuickTime Conversion,
and I can click right here.

00:33:38.900 --> 00:33:40.910
And in addition to all the
other codecs we support,

00:33:40.920 --> 00:33:41.620
here's 3GPP.

00:33:41.700 --> 00:33:45.340
If I select that,
I can go a little further.

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:48.840
Instead of using the default options,
go into the settings.

00:33:48.840 --> 00:33:53.040
And the guys in engineering did an
incredibly elegant job of presenting

00:33:53.040 --> 00:33:57.690
all the myriad of options that exist
for you to tailor the 3G file to

00:33:57.900 --> 00:34:01.630
the particular network you're on,
or the particular format you want to use,

00:34:01.630 --> 00:34:05.360
whether it's just the general versions,
the profiles of 3GPP,

00:34:05.470 --> 00:34:08.740
video information with sliders,
audio with sliders.

00:34:08.860 --> 00:34:10.640
There's no better way to
adjust this stuff than just

00:34:10.820 --> 00:34:11.920
grabbing and dragging a slider.

00:34:11.920 --> 00:34:15.270
And text is really important
in the Japanese market,

00:34:15.270 --> 00:34:19.280
scrolling text,
support for emoji and other capabilities.

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:23.410
So what I would normally do now is
just dial up the settings I want,

00:34:23.410 --> 00:34:25.540
hit Export, it would happen.

00:34:25.540 --> 00:34:27.880
And then what I would get is a 3G file.

00:34:27.880 --> 00:34:31.800
The 3G file of this movie
is just over 200 kilobytes,

00:34:31.800 --> 00:34:34.550
from almost 200 megabytes
to 200 kilobytes,

00:34:34.810 --> 00:34:35.640
using this format.

00:34:35.640 --> 00:34:40.590
And when I was in Japan last week,
we actually... We actually did send

00:34:40.610 --> 00:34:44.020
it over the wireless internet and
it downloaded right to my phone.

00:34:44.100 --> 00:34:45.820
We can't do that here.

00:34:46.110 --> 00:34:49.530
But what I have,
if we can switch over to the visualizer.

00:34:55.750 --> 00:34:56.300
There we go.

00:34:56.330 --> 00:35:01.460
What I have is my,
this is actually my phone,

00:35:01.460 --> 00:35:03.510
and we have that video clip on it.

00:35:03.610 --> 00:35:07.400
So what I'll do is I'll just play that,
and you can see what it looks like.

00:35:07.440 --> 00:35:13.150
It's accessing the
SD card where it lives.

00:35:13.180 --> 00:35:18.960
Can you hear that?

00:35:29.330 --> 00:35:32.790
So, 200 kilobit file,
and just transfer it over.

00:35:32.920 --> 00:35:33.200
Thanks.

00:35:37.300 --> 00:35:41.000
The coolest thing is about this,
when we were in Japan doing

00:35:41.430 --> 00:35:44.140
this press briefing,
we were able to right there in front

00:35:44.240 --> 00:35:45.870
of all the press do these demos live.

00:35:45.950 --> 00:35:47.930
I mean,
we were able to capture some content,

00:35:48.010 --> 00:35:51.130
we were able to push the content
up to an iDisc and email the

00:35:51.130 --> 00:35:52.810
URL of that movie to my phone.

00:35:52.810 --> 00:35:56.120
I clicked it on my phone,
it progressively downloaded to my phone,

00:35:56.120 --> 00:35:58.370
I watched it as it happened,
we took some video of the

00:35:58.370 --> 00:35:59.540
audience and moved it.

00:35:59.590 --> 00:36:01.380
It was really,
it was like doing things over

00:36:01.410 --> 00:36:04.080
the internet but with no wires,
and it really works and it

00:36:04.180 --> 00:36:07.920
represents kind of the center
of the set of activities.

