00:37:23.300 --> 00:37:28.440
So, the last 10 months have been a
very important year for QuickTime.

00:37:28.440 --> 00:37:32.430
Really a year of building a
foundation of technology on which

00:37:32.430 --> 00:37:34.300
we would build our future products.

00:37:34.300 --> 00:37:38.440
And in the last year we
built a complete end-to-end

00:37:38.440 --> 00:37:43.560
solution for the MPEG-4 format,
including the live broadcast tool,

00:37:43.800 --> 00:37:45.300
the QuickTime Broadcaster.

00:37:45.300 --> 00:37:49.300
We've got the streaming server,
which now supports MPEG-4.

00:37:49.300 --> 00:37:53.350
We've got the QuickTime player,
and we've created a whole

00:37:53.350 --> 00:37:54.300
end-to-end solution.

00:37:54.300 --> 00:37:58.300
And I think it's been, first of all,
it was an incredible amount of work.

00:37:58.300 --> 00:38:03.570
But I think as you see the 3G stuff,
you start to get the idea of some

00:38:03.570 --> 00:38:06.300
of the interesting convergence
possibilities that arise.

00:38:06.300 --> 00:38:10.340
And I think you can see from the
relatively simple and simplistic

00:38:10.340 --> 00:38:14.300
even interface that we're
providing in the standard players,

00:38:14.300 --> 00:38:18.680
that there's a lot of opportunity for
you as a software developer to come in

00:38:18.950 --> 00:38:23.690
and build more finely tuned solutions,
and to really orient yourself towards

00:38:23.690 --> 00:38:27.630
some of these new markets where
the PC and the consumer electronics

00:38:27.710 --> 00:38:29.300
industries are starting to come together.

00:38:29.300 --> 00:38:33.110
The consumer electronics
industry knows all about building

00:38:33.110 --> 00:38:35.290
things into the small devices.

00:38:35.300 --> 00:38:38.380
But they really,
really need your help when it comes

00:38:38.380 --> 00:38:42.230
to building polished solutions that
bring the Internet and the consumer

00:38:42.230 --> 00:38:43.300
electronics world closer together.

00:38:43.300 --> 00:38:48.260
And this is what I think is a
great opportunity for all of you.

00:38:48.420 --> 00:38:52.300
So, now I'd like to turn attention
to what's coming down the pike.

00:38:52.300 --> 00:38:56.010
Things we're working on for
Panther and in the coming few months

00:38:56.010 --> 00:38:58.220
that we'll be able to deliver to you.

00:38:59.650 --> 00:39:03.440
The first thing I want to talk
about is QuickTime for Java.

00:39:03.480 --> 00:39:06.590
As you know,
QuickTime for Java exists today.

00:39:06.590 --> 00:39:08.390
We've had it available
for a couple of years.

00:39:08.400 --> 00:39:09.790
It's got a very rich feature set.

00:39:09.790 --> 00:39:12.540
We're making some pretty
significant upgrades to the system.

00:39:12.540 --> 00:39:16.850
The first thing tracks some changes,
fairly major changes that are happening

00:39:16.850 --> 00:39:19.050
in Apple's overall support for Java.

00:39:19.100 --> 00:39:23.010
The new version of QuickTime for
Java is compatible with Java 1.4.1.

00:39:23.020 --> 00:39:23.990
Very important.

00:39:23.990 --> 00:39:27.100
It's the latest version from
Sun that's widely deployed.

00:39:27.740 --> 00:39:33.900
It integrates fully with Java's
AWT and swing components.

00:39:33.960 --> 00:39:36.790
Very important to the
developers we've talked to,

00:39:36.790 --> 00:39:40.640
we received a lot of feedback about this,
is that we wanted to see the

00:39:40.640 --> 00:39:45.390
Java APIs in QuickTime conform a
little bit more closely to the kinds of

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:47.700
metaphors that Java programmers expect.

00:39:47.900 --> 00:39:50.430
And this is things like
factories and players and

00:39:50.490 --> 00:39:52.580
drawers and that kind of a model.

00:39:52.580 --> 00:39:55.800
And so we've made some API changes
that will support this new metaphor.

00:39:55.920 --> 00:39:59.690
And of course,
you can still access all the

00:39:59.850 --> 00:40:05.500
C APIs for QuickTime through JNI,
which is the standard model for

00:40:05.880 --> 00:40:08.650
how Java connects to C APIs.

00:40:08.900 --> 00:40:12.060
If you've got existing apps, well,
you're going to have to make some

00:40:12.060 --> 00:40:15.160
small changes to those applications
in all likelihood to be able to make

00:40:15.270 --> 00:40:16.940
them run in the new world order.

00:40:16.940 --> 00:40:20.650
But you can continue to use Java 1.3.1,
and we're continuing to

00:40:20.780 --> 00:40:23.330
ship that in the systems,
and so all of your existing

00:40:23.330 --> 00:40:25.240
applications will still be compatible.

00:40:25.260 --> 00:40:29.980
But there are opportunities to do
new kinds of integration with Java,

00:40:30.060 --> 00:40:35.210
and new kinds of capabilities enabled by
Java 1.4 that you'll need to switch over

00:40:35.220 --> 00:40:37.040
to support if you want those features.

00:40:37.160 --> 00:40:41.480
We will make these capabilities
available for Mac OS X and for Windows,

00:40:41.480 --> 00:40:43.980
and we've begun seeding already.

00:40:43.980 --> 00:40:48.030
As long as you're a member of ADC,
Apple's Developer Connection Program,

00:40:48.030 --> 00:40:51.420
you can go up to the website and
you can find out how to get onto the

00:40:51.420 --> 00:40:53.720
seed list and get the software today.

00:40:55.250 --> 00:40:57.700
The next thing I want to talk
about is QuickTime for Cocoa.

00:40:57.840 --> 00:41:02.380
As you know,
Cocoa supports QuickTime through

00:41:02.380 --> 00:41:04.680
a couple of built-in classes.

00:41:04.780 --> 00:41:06.460
We've got NSMovie and NSMovieView.

00:41:06.460 --> 00:41:09.420
They use the standard kind
of object-oriented model

00:41:09.420 --> 00:41:11.870
where you've got model,
view, controller,

00:41:11.870 --> 00:41:16.180
and we've created a similar separation
in QuickTime in NSMovie and NSMovieView.

00:41:17.180 --> 00:41:20.810
We are going to be adding several
new classes to our support for

00:41:20.810 --> 00:41:23.060
QuickTime for Cocoa programmers.

00:41:23.060 --> 00:41:24.470
Yes, long awaited.

00:41:24.510 --> 00:41:28.670
It's going to give you a lot more access
to the lower-level data structures and

00:41:28.670 --> 00:41:31.020
some of the lower-level capabilities.

00:41:31.020 --> 00:41:34.840
Hopefully, this will all be packaged up
into an easy-to-consume format.

00:41:34.840 --> 00:41:38.360
Frank mentioned there's 2,400
different APIs for QuickTime.

00:41:38.360 --> 00:41:41.950
If you're just getting started,
if your orientation is around

00:41:41.950 --> 00:41:45.640
building an application that
takes advantage of QuickTime,

00:41:45.640 --> 00:41:47.160
you probably don't want
to look for a quick time.

00:41:47.160 --> 00:41:51.020
You want to learn 2,400 new
APIs before you can do anything.

00:41:51.020 --> 00:41:54.000
This is going to go a long
ways to making that task much,

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:54.930
much easier.

00:41:55.200 --> 00:41:57.650
As with the Java work,
you can also combine this

00:41:57.780 --> 00:41:59.340
with the traditional C API.

00:41:59.340 --> 00:42:02.300
So if you know those details,
or you need to get more advanced

00:42:02.650 --> 00:42:05.750
functionality that we haven't
yet revealed in the Cocoa world,

00:42:05.750 --> 00:42:07.330
you'll still be able to do that.

00:42:07.340 --> 00:42:10.990
We haven't yet begun seeding this work.

00:42:11.050 --> 00:42:14.690
It's not in your Panther packages,
but we're going to begin very shortly.

00:42:14.690 --> 00:42:17.520
And so if you're interested in this,
I would encourage you to

00:42:17.530 --> 00:42:19.180
contact Guillermo Ortiz.

00:42:19.200 --> 00:42:25.490
He's providing all of the developer
assistance inside of developer relations,

00:42:25.490 --> 00:42:27.270
and he'll make sure
you're on the seed list,

00:42:27.370 --> 00:42:29.660
and we'll let you know just as
soon as the software is available.

00:42:29.660 --> 00:42:32.420
It's very exciting,
and we're really looking forward

00:42:32.420 --> 00:42:35.520
to seeing what you'll be able
to do with QuickTime in Cocoa.

00:42:37.210 --> 00:42:38.740
The next thing I want to
talk about is performance.

00:42:38.810 --> 00:42:43.300
Multimedia really isn't much of a
phenomenon without good performance.

00:42:43.300 --> 00:42:48.080
And we spend a lot of time at
Apple working on performance.

00:42:48.080 --> 00:42:51.820
And this breaks down to
several different categories.

00:42:51.820 --> 00:42:54.170
Certainly there is the domain of codecs.

00:42:54.320 --> 00:42:56.820
We've got a whole stable of codecs.

00:42:56.980 --> 00:43:01.410
And with every release of QuickTime,
we try to make an investment

00:43:01.410 --> 00:43:04.950
in improving the performance of
the ones that we're hearing from

00:43:04.950 --> 00:43:06.520
you are most important to you.

00:43:06.820 --> 00:43:09.940
And the areas where we can see from
the ways that QuickTime is being

00:43:09.940 --> 00:43:12.830
used are getting the most pressure.

00:43:12.860 --> 00:43:16.910
And in the last several months,
we've been making significant

00:43:17.010 --> 00:43:20.120
enhancements with this
standard set of codecs.

00:43:20.280 --> 00:43:24.430
And that's a real important
part of what we're working on.

00:43:24.460 --> 00:43:29.080
The second area has to do not with
the side of getting to the screen,

00:43:29.080 --> 00:43:32.220
but the part where you get the data
from the disk and into the system.

00:43:32.220 --> 00:43:36.280
I'll be talking in a minute about
some higher resolution video.

00:43:36.380 --> 00:43:37.650
And video work we've been doing.

00:43:37.660 --> 00:43:42.300
One of the really important elements
of working with high-res video and

00:43:42.300 --> 00:43:47.220
uncompressed video is being able to
manage the super intensive data I.O.

00:43:47.220 --> 00:43:48.610
that's associated with these formats.

00:43:48.620 --> 00:43:51.720
We've been doing a lot of work
in the plumbing of QuickTime in

00:43:51.840 --> 00:43:55.190
the areas of the data handlers,
the software that gets the data

00:43:55.200 --> 00:43:58.790
from the disks and hands it off to
QuickTime in a timed sort of a way,

00:43:58.790 --> 00:44:00.160
a synchronized way.

00:44:00.160 --> 00:44:02.820
And the video media handlers,
which are responsible for moving the

00:44:02.820 --> 00:44:04.420
data through the QuickTime system.

00:44:04.420 --> 00:44:06.360
We've been doing a lot
of work here to be able.

00:44:06.360 --> 00:44:10.950
To make QuickTime be able to keep up with
the really high data rates that you'd

00:44:11.060 --> 00:44:13.860
associate with uncompressed HD res video.

00:44:13.860 --> 00:44:15.620
And we'll talk a little bit
more about that shortly.

00:44:15.620 --> 00:44:20.580
The last area I want to talk about
relates to QuickTime and its usability in

00:44:20.580 --> 00:44:23.880
a multi-threaded application environment.

00:44:23.880 --> 00:44:27.260
As most of you probably know,
putting QuickTime in a

00:44:27.320 --> 00:44:31.480
multi-threaded environment has
been kind of a no-no to date.

00:44:31.500 --> 00:44:34.030
There are a lot of aspects
of QuickTime which have

00:44:34.050 --> 00:44:35.550
not been multi-threaded.

00:44:36.340 --> 00:44:38.500
There are thread safe,
there's a lot of aspects of

00:44:38.500 --> 00:44:41.450
the lower level system which
haven't been thread safe to date.

00:44:41.580 --> 00:44:46.520
But we felt that one of the most
important areas where we could provide

00:44:46.520 --> 00:44:50.040
some substantial improvements in the
overall performance and responsiveness

00:44:50.130 --> 00:44:55.910
of the system would come if we could
unlock some of those blockers for you.

00:44:56.020 --> 00:44:59.170
And so we've been doing a lot
of work inside of QuickTime to

00:44:59.170 --> 00:45:02.960
be able to allow you to start
putting QuickTime functionality

00:45:03.180 --> 00:45:04.650
on separate threads.

00:45:05.240 --> 00:45:06.320
Whether this is due to a single
thread or a single block.

00:45:06.320 --> 00:45:09.790
Whether it's doing background
compression or background

00:45:09.790 --> 00:45:11.970
renders or exports or imports.

00:45:12.080 --> 00:45:15.800
A whole range of operations
that are really important for

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:20.080
building high performance and
highly responsive applications.

00:45:20.080 --> 00:45:23.240
And we're going to be delivering
this stuff in Panther and I would

00:45:23.240 --> 00:45:25.560
encourage you to go to some of the
other sessions where they'll be talking

00:45:25.560 --> 00:45:28.080
about the details in much greater depth.

00:45:28.080 --> 00:45:35.010
But that's a really critical piece of
our work for Panther in QuickTime 6.4.

00:45:35.850 --> 00:45:40.600
So, the next thing I want to talk about
is the QuickTime streaming server.

00:45:40.600 --> 00:45:43.680
We introduced the QuickTime streaming
server a couple of years ago,

00:45:43.680 --> 00:45:46.940
and it's really been very,
very successful for Apple.

00:45:46.940 --> 00:45:50.040
I want to tell you very
quickly what's in it.

00:45:50.040 --> 00:45:51.920
So the server is a full function server.

00:45:51.920 --> 00:45:54.280
It's an industrial strength server.

00:45:54.330 --> 00:45:56.120
It's able to support live streams.

00:45:56.240 --> 00:45:58.480
It's able to support video on demand.

00:45:58.770 --> 00:46:01.160
You can connect the
QuickTime broadcaster to it and

00:46:01.280 --> 00:46:03.170
do all the replication of streams.

00:46:03.180 --> 00:46:05.890
So you can do multicast,
you can do unicast,

00:46:05.900 --> 00:46:07.480
all that kind of stuff.

00:46:07.480 --> 00:46:12.430
We also built into the system support
for our proprietary skip protection

00:46:12.430 --> 00:46:14.190
and instant on technologies.

00:46:14.310 --> 00:46:17.140
These technologies make the
experience of streaming much,

00:46:17.190 --> 00:46:22.250
much easier and more enjoyable for
consumers working on the internet.

00:46:22.280 --> 00:46:25.940
Skip protection basically allows you to
utilize excess bandwidth of the network

00:46:25.940 --> 00:46:29.380
to be able to buffer the content ahead,
so that when there are

00:46:29.380 --> 00:46:33.440
glitches in the network,
as there typically are, packets are lost,

00:46:33.610 --> 00:46:38.670
it provides enough of a... enough
of a buffering ahead so that you

00:46:38.670 --> 00:46:42.030
can go back and get the packets
before they're actually needed,

00:46:42.060 --> 00:46:45.830
so the customer never even notices
that the packets were lost or

00:46:45.860 --> 00:46:47.380
that the network was flaky.

00:46:47.570 --> 00:46:49.820
The instant on, of course,
provides the experience of not having

00:46:49.820 --> 00:46:52.380
to wait when you connect to a stream.

00:46:52.380 --> 00:46:56.810
The buffering messages basically go away,
and it's pretty much like what you

00:46:57.110 --> 00:47:00.280
would experience if you were playing
the files on your local hard drive

00:47:00.280 --> 00:47:02.020
if you've got the network bandwidth.

00:47:02.060 --> 00:47:04.430
We've got a very rich Apache style, plus,
we've got a very rich

00:47:04.500 --> 00:47:05.960
Apache style plug-in architecture
for the streaming server.

00:47:06.020 --> 00:47:08.150
If you haven't looked at
this and you're interested in

00:47:08.290 --> 00:47:12.270
server-oriented media operations,
I would strongly encourage you to go to

00:47:12.280 --> 00:47:14.560
the sessions and hear more about this.

00:47:14.650 --> 00:47:17.770
The plug-in architecture allows you
to customize and extend all kinds of

00:47:17.770 --> 00:47:19.600
functions in the streaming server.

00:47:19.840 --> 00:47:21.120
Really cool.

00:47:21.180 --> 00:47:24.180
This is all built into Mac OS X Server,
but in addition,

00:47:24.580 --> 00:47:27.630
Apple decided back in the beginning
we were going to make the software

00:47:27.690 --> 00:47:29.430
available through an open source project.

00:47:29.520 --> 00:47:33.430
We call it Apple's Public Source License,
also known as DARPA.

00:47:33.460 --> 00:47:33.990
We're going to make the software
available through a server

00:47:33.990 --> 00:47:34.430
called the Darwin Server.

00:47:34.580 --> 00:47:40.820
And you can go out and download
the software and you can port it

00:47:40.860 --> 00:47:42.800
to whatever platform you want.

00:47:42.800 --> 00:47:47.220
It's already available in binary
form for all the major OS platforms.

00:47:47.220 --> 00:47:49.570
And this has been very, very successful.

00:47:49.570 --> 00:47:53.820
We've had several hundred thousand
developers download and use the server.

00:47:55.800 --> 00:49:36.900
[Transcript missing]

00:49:39.200 --> 00:49:43.430
Now, we've been having some network
challenges over the last 24 hours,

00:49:43.530 --> 00:49:47.340
so just give them a
break if it has trouble.

00:49:47.340 --> 00:49:51.620
Okay, so as Tim kind of mentioned,
QuickTime QTSS Publisher is really

00:49:51.670 --> 00:49:55.780
designed to solve those problems where
you've got your media all encoded,

00:49:55.780 --> 00:49:57.290
it's all ready to go,
now it's time to get

00:49:57.290 --> 00:49:58.220
it up on the internet.

00:49:58.220 --> 00:49:59.060
What do you do?

00:49:59.060 --> 00:50:00.120
You go and FTP it up.

00:50:00.320 --> 00:50:02.020
Oh, God, I forgot to hint it.

00:50:02.070 --> 00:50:04.390
Hint it, put it back up.

00:50:05.490 --> 00:50:06.480
What's the URL for that?

00:50:06.480 --> 00:50:08.110
It's like it's always been
complicated for people,

00:50:08.120 --> 00:50:10.590
so we really tried to simplify
that whole process for people who

00:50:10.590 --> 00:50:15.340
are responsible for making the
content available on the internet.

00:50:17.370 --> 00:50:19.750
So here's the application.

00:50:20.020 --> 00:50:22.460
When you bring it up,
you're going to see your media library.

00:50:22.460 --> 00:50:25.100
You can kind of view this
as kind of the staging area,

00:50:25.100 --> 00:50:27.680
or it's basically the library of
all of your stuff that could be

00:50:27.680 --> 00:50:29.490
made available for the internet.

00:50:29.610 --> 00:50:31.950
It's not yet available on the internet.

00:50:32.020 --> 00:50:34.280
This is just a place where
you kind of do all your work.

00:50:34.380 --> 00:50:38.080
You can view things hierarchically.

00:50:38.080 --> 00:50:41.680
You can organize things in any kind
of directory structure you want to.

00:50:42.500 --> 00:50:45.500
You can click over here
to the View All view,

00:50:45.500 --> 00:50:48.470
and you can see everything
in your entire library.

00:50:48.810 --> 00:50:51.930
So once you've decided you're ready
to put something on the internet,

00:50:51.980 --> 00:50:54.010
just click on that.

00:50:54.160 --> 00:50:56.220
And then move over to the
settings for that application.

00:50:56.380 --> 00:50:59.630
So if anybody's ever tried to put
something up on their streaming

00:50:59.640 --> 00:51:02.100
server and had to go through the
whole process of hinting a movie,

00:51:02.100 --> 00:51:06.100
we basically have now made it one click.

00:51:06.160 --> 00:51:06.560
So you're done.

00:51:06.560 --> 00:51:08.770
This movie is now up on the server.

00:51:08.850 --> 00:51:15.840
It's showing me the URL that is necessary
for the viewer to look at this movie.

00:51:15.840 --> 00:51:18.000
So I'll click on that and it'll actually
preview it for me in the player.

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:22.820
So that is a lot easier.

00:51:24.100 --> 00:51:26.090
Great.

00:51:28.160 --> 00:51:35.480
So the second problem that people
tend to have is setting up playlists.

00:51:35.480 --> 00:51:38.020
So I'm going to go back to media.

00:51:38.020 --> 00:51:40.000
This application lets you
manage all of your playlists.

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:44.360
You can manage MP3 playlists,
which are using Icecast,

00:51:44.360 --> 00:51:48.040
Shoutcast protocol,
or you can manage your

00:51:48.040 --> 00:51:50.250
QuickTime playlists,
which can be movies or audio or

00:51:50.300 --> 00:51:51.760
any kind of QuickTime content.

00:51:51.760 --> 00:51:55.830
So I'm going to show you how easy
it is to create an MP3 playlist.

00:51:56.750 --> 00:51:58.970
Let's click New Playlist.

00:51:59.340 --> 00:52:03.310
Let's say I want to set
up a listening party for

00:52:03.690 --> 00:52:06.530
A new Linkin Park CD that came out.

00:52:06.620 --> 00:52:09.190
We do this all the time at Apple.

00:52:09.390 --> 00:52:13.600
Click new playlist, I name it,
go find all the content I would like,

00:52:13.760 --> 00:52:16.460
and I'm just going to
select the entire album.

00:52:17.740 --> 00:52:21.540
Those actually are the
real names for these songs.

00:52:21.540 --> 00:52:23.570
I dragged them in here.

00:52:23.870 --> 00:52:27.610
So I could click start
and it would just work.

00:52:27.620 --> 00:52:30.020
The playlist would be up and
available on the internet.

00:52:30.060 --> 00:52:32.610
But when you're doing a listening party,
you tend to want to schedule things.

00:52:32.610 --> 00:52:35.250
You want to play at 3:30 on Friday,
right?

00:52:35.470 --> 00:52:42.910
So we've added functionality to let you
schedule when the playlist should start.

00:52:43.090 --> 00:52:46.620
So I could say I want
this to play on July 1st.

00:52:46.620 --> 00:52:49.310
I want it I'd like to start at 3:30 p.m.

00:52:49.500 --> 00:52:58.200
[Transcript missing]

00:53:00.300 --> 00:53:05.480
and then going back to the media list.

00:53:06.260 --> 00:53:10.700
The other problem people tend to have is
that they've got all this content ready,

00:53:10.700 --> 00:53:12.860
they think they've got
it hidden properly,

00:53:13.030 --> 00:53:14.240
they've got RTSP URLs.

00:53:14.320 --> 00:53:17.290
It's always been a real pain to
kind of get all the HTML all set up.

00:53:17.370 --> 00:53:20.080
So I'm going to show you
now how you can do that.

00:53:20.590 --> 00:53:23.340
If you go over to your links view,
this is going to show you everything

00:53:23.340 --> 00:53:24.420
that is available on the internet.

00:53:24.420 --> 00:53:27.500
So I've got all of these
playlists that are available.

00:53:27.600 --> 00:53:31.410
I'm going to go over to the Avril CD.

00:53:31.500 --> 00:53:34.470
I can drop in a custom image.

00:53:34.500 --> 00:53:37.200
This is what's going to
show up on the webpage.

00:53:37.790 --> 00:53:44.660
I can also really easily generate
ref movies for doing multi bandwidth.

00:53:44.760 --> 00:53:47.040
So you've got people who
are listening on modems,

00:53:47.170 --> 00:53:49.150
people on DSL, and people on LAN.

00:53:49.230 --> 00:53:51.670
And basically it's just a matter
of dragging things over there.

00:53:51.730 --> 00:53:52.780
It's really easy to do.

00:53:52.780 --> 00:53:55.290
I'm not going to do that right now.

00:53:55.620 --> 00:54:00.110
The next thing is we will actually
generate the HTML for you.

00:54:00.120 --> 00:54:02.740
So this HTML is valid if you
were to take it and drag it into

00:54:02.750 --> 00:54:07.220
Dreamweaver or BBEdit or your
favorite web authoring application.

00:54:07.290 --> 00:54:08.600
It would just work.

00:54:08.600 --> 00:54:14.670
Let me move on to one last thing.

00:54:15.330 --> 00:54:18.910
So we've also made it really
easy to generate web pages.

00:54:19.120 --> 00:54:23.410
So select a couple of items,
click web page.

00:54:23.410 --> 00:54:25.550
Got the option to select a template.

00:54:25.550 --> 00:54:28.170
We're going to ship with
a bunch of templates,

00:54:28.210 --> 00:54:31.080
but we're using an open
standard called XSL.

00:54:31.080 --> 00:54:34.500
So for most of you professionals,
