00:59:18.550 --> 00:59:21.550
But it's really big,
it's really expensive,

00:59:21.780 --> 00:59:25.190
and that means it's not
going to be widely available.

00:59:27.280 --> 00:59:31.580
As Steve mentioned yesterday,
we find ourselves on occasion

00:59:31.580 --> 00:59:34.370
working with this other company
that he has some involvement with,

00:59:34.500 --> 00:59:34.800
Pixar.

00:59:34.800 --> 00:59:38.130
And they've been telling us about
the problems that they have when

00:59:38.240 --> 00:59:40.200
they're working with their content.

00:59:40.390 --> 00:59:44.110
And the problems basically, to us,
sounded very similar to the kinds of

00:59:44.200 --> 00:59:47.540
problems that everybody working with
HD content is going to start to have.

00:59:47.700 --> 00:59:50.240
And we decided we were going
to get involved and see what we

00:59:50.240 --> 00:59:51.670
could do to try and help out.

00:59:51.740 --> 00:59:53.500
This is an interesting space for Apple.

00:59:53.700 --> 00:59:57.280
We care a great deal about
content creation and publishing,

00:59:57.290 --> 01:00:00.200
not just for consumers,
but also for the professional space.

01:00:00.200 --> 01:00:03.180
It's very important to us
because it's often the harbinger,

01:00:03.180 --> 01:00:09.180
the leading edge of what will be
consumer technology in the years to come.

01:00:09.400 --> 01:00:12.290
And so we like to practice
our skills in the pro space,

01:00:12.290 --> 01:00:14.130
and hope that those,
as those things become

01:00:14.130 --> 01:00:16.280
more and more mainstream,
we'll be able to leverage

01:00:16.280 --> 01:00:19.200
the know-how that we acquired
trying to solve these problems.

01:00:19.430 --> 01:00:23.000
So we built this codec called Pixlet.

01:00:23.200 --> 01:00:26.580
I want to go back to the slides, please.

01:00:30.370 --> 01:00:34.260
Pixlet is this really interesting codec,
and I don't think we've ever seen

01:00:34.260 --> 01:00:35.680
anything that's quite like it.

01:00:35.740 --> 01:00:39.650
The first thing we wanted to
design was something that could

01:00:39.650 --> 01:00:42.080
handle studio-grade image quality.

01:00:42.080 --> 01:00:44.360
And this meant,
not that I thought it looked good,

01:00:44.360 --> 01:00:47.870
but it meant that it could pass the
sniff test with people at Pixar.

01:00:47.880 --> 01:00:50.220
People who do this for a living.

01:00:50.220 --> 01:00:53.240
In order to be able to
achieve this quality,

01:00:53.240 --> 01:00:57.280
we felt that the way we needed to
get there was to leverage some very,

01:00:57.360 --> 01:01:02.110
very powerful still image technology
that's built into JPEG 2000,

01:01:02.170 --> 01:01:06.040
but we took it and built a proprietary
version of this because what we

01:01:06.040 --> 01:01:11.470
encountered was that the standard
algorithms are not computationally

01:01:11.490 --> 01:01:14.320
sort of feasible on today's hardware.

01:01:14.320 --> 01:01:18.020
So we did a whole bunch of work
to tune the wavelet in order to

01:01:18.170 --> 01:01:22.130
be able to run it in real time
on today's hardware platforms.

01:01:22.140 --> 01:01:24.960
If you tried to do this
experiment using JPEG 2000,

01:01:24.980 --> 01:01:27.650
many of the characteristics
you'd be able to achieve,

01:01:27.870 --> 01:01:29.440
but many of them you would not.

01:01:29.500 --> 01:01:32.290
And in particular,
the performance benchmark you'd need

01:01:32.290 --> 01:01:35.900
to meet to be able to have this be
widely usable would not be possible.

01:01:35.920 --> 01:01:38.640
So we did a whole bunch of
work optimizing both for

01:01:38.640 --> 01:01:42.520
the G4 and G5 architectures,
but also work in the core of

01:01:42.520 --> 01:01:46.100
the math to enable the wavelet
algorithm to be efficient enough.

01:01:46.330 --> 01:01:48.580
The codec supports arbitrary resolution.

01:01:48.580 --> 01:01:52.200
It accepts very deep color,
as Steve mentioned.

01:01:52.200 --> 01:01:55.060
Certainly you can put 8-bit per
pixel channel color in there,

01:01:55.130 --> 01:01:57.240
but you can go deeper
if that's important.

01:01:57.240 --> 01:01:58.800
And it's a variable compression.

01:01:59.400 --> 01:02:00.420
It's a very simple algorithm.

01:02:00.420 --> 01:02:02.370
So you can use 20 to 1.

01:02:02.380 --> 01:02:03.370
You can go up to 40 to 1.

01:02:03.520 --> 01:02:05.860
You can go outside that range,
but my experience is that most people

01:02:06.130 --> 01:02:07.540
are going to stay in that range.

01:02:07.580 --> 01:02:10.250
And that means that it
ends up producing for,

01:02:10.250 --> 01:02:13.410
say, half HD resolution,
a data rate that's about the

01:02:13.490 --> 01:02:15.500
same data rate as DV content.

01:02:15.500 --> 01:02:17.310
So it's not low data rate.

01:02:17.320 --> 01:02:18.860
It's not an internet file format.

01:02:18.860 --> 01:02:21.800
But it's a format that's very,
very usable in the studio.

01:02:21.800 --> 01:02:25.360
So let me go back to the demo
machine and show you what the same

01:02:25.360 --> 01:02:27.700
clip looks like encoded in Pixlet.

