01:04:31.820 --> 01:04:35.060
So the next topic I'm going to
talk about is color management.

01:04:35.090 --> 01:04:38.700
Now, first of all,
a little bit of background about what

01:04:38.700 --> 01:04:40.300
this color management problem is.

01:04:40.340 --> 01:04:43.390
Basically,
every device that captures images,

01:04:43.390 --> 01:04:47.530
captures in a digital format,
captures them with certain

01:04:47.670 --> 01:04:51.100
assumptions about what it means,
what the digital values that are

01:04:51.100 --> 01:04:53.510
associated with the pixels actually mean.

01:04:53.720 --> 01:04:58.090
And of significance is the whole
question of what does the color,

01:04:58.090 --> 01:05:02.140
a certain color, end up mapping to in
terms of the pixel values.

01:05:02.150 --> 01:05:05.650
Now, the unfortunate or just the
harsh reality of the world is

01:05:06.050 --> 01:05:09.300
that from device to device,
whether it's a camera

01:05:09.330 --> 01:05:13.010
as in an input device,
or a screen, an output device,

01:05:13.010 --> 01:05:15.930
or a piece of paper
coming out of a printer,

01:05:15.930 --> 01:05:17.850
this is highly variable.

01:05:18.030 --> 01:05:22.220
And in addition to that,
the language of color that has been

01:05:22.220 --> 01:05:26.970
developed in each of these different
market segments is very different.

01:05:26.970 --> 01:05:30.710
Creates a tremendous problem if
you're working in a professional

01:05:30.740 --> 01:05:34.760
environment where color accuracy
and color fidelity is important.

01:05:34.760 --> 01:05:39.760
So Apple created a technology that
allows you to solve this problem.

01:05:39.760 --> 01:05:44.910
We basically modeled the source
color profile of the source media,

01:05:45.110 --> 01:05:50.040
source device,
and we modeled the destination device.

01:05:50.040 --> 01:05:55.640
And then we apply transformations to the
pixels to be able to adjust and normalize

01:05:55.640 --> 01:05:58.140
and produce a calibrated result,
which is very, very important.

01:05:58.140 --> 01:06:00.260
So, in the end,
we have a result which is accurate.

01:06:00.290 --> 01:06:01.760
It works really, really well.

01:06:02.090 --> 01:06:05.520
It's been widely adopted in the
professional publishing domain.

01:06:06.820 --> 01:06:10.700
But, you know, it was traditionally
quite an advanced feature.

01:06:10.700 --> 01:06:15.380
When we brought this out in 1995,
it was computationally pretty expensive.

01:06:15.390 --> 01:06:18.310
And if color wasn't super
critical to what you were doing,

01:06:18.580 --> 01:06:21.560
it wasn't something you were
likely to be willing to pay the

01:06:21.560 --> 01:06:23.500
computational cost to support.

01:06:23.500 --> 01:06:26.380
And so it was an opt-in feature.

01:06:26.380 --> 01:06:29.560
Now let me tell you the
second part of the story.

01:06:29.580 --> 01:06:32.180
We built these technologies
into QuickTime called Graphic

01:06:32.260 --> 01:06:33.400
Importers and Exporters.

01:06:33.540 --> 01:06:35.470
Very powerful, very easy to use.

01:06:35.630 --> 01:06:41.180
Allows you to open or save to a
whole range of still image formats.

01:06:41.560 --> 01:06:44.110
QuickTime supports a whole bunch of them.

01:06:44.590 --> 01:06:48.210
And, you know,
we're adding new ones all the time.

01:06:48.340 --> 01:06:54.120
A lot of you have written importers,
exporters to support your own formats.

01:06:54.350 --> 01:06:58.260
One of the things about this is
that these images tend to come to

01:06:58.260 --> 01:07:02.600
you tagged with different color
profiles that are supposed to be

01:07:02.650 --> 01:07:05.880
used in managing this color workflow.

01:07:06.720 --> 01:07:09.360
We've provided APIs inside of
the graphic importers to be

01:07:09.360 --> 01:07:12.960
able to read these profiles,
and then on export to be

01:07:12.980 --> 01:07:14.760
able to write them out.

01:07:16.200 --> 01:07:18.040
Hello.

01:07:18.070 --> 01:07:20.700
But it was up to you to
go and make those calls,

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:24.510
pull the data out,
and be able to write it back.

01:07:26.420 --> 01:07:29.330
Our experience is this has led to
a very inconsistent experience,

01:07:29.340 --> 01:07:30.640
and I want to show you that right now.

01:07:30.660 --> 01:07:33.660
Hello.

01:07:33.660 --> 01:07:35.740
We're going to go to the demo machine.

01:07:35.740 --> 01:07:38.540
Oh, okay.

01:07:38.660 --> 01:07:40.690
We'll just go to the demo machine.

01:07:45.300 --> 01:07:53.100
So the first thing I want to
do is I've got this Nemo image.

01:07:55.150 --> 01:07:56.680
And I'm going to open
it up with Photoshop.

01:07:56.710 --> 01:07:58.140
Photoshop's kind of the gold standard.

01:07:58.140 --> 01:08:00.010
They get it right.

01:08:00.170 --> 01:08:03.410
So I want to show you what it
looks like when it's correct.

01:08:07.530 --> 01:08:08.740
So there you go.

01:08:08.750 --> 01:08:11.850
Now I'm going to open
the same image in BBEdit.

01:08:12.060 --> 01:08:15.840
Now,
you don't expect BBEdit to get it right,

01:08:15.850 --> 01:08:17.490
because it's not really
an imaging application.

01:08:17.510 --> 01:08:21.060
And if you look here,
what you can see is that the colors in

01:08:21.080 --> 01:08:26.360
the BBEdit version are much darker than
the colors in the Photoshop version.

01:08:26.360 --> 01:08:29.490
And the Photoshop version is correct,
and this is wrong.

01:08:29.490 --> 01:08:30.840
I don't mean to slam BBEdit.

01:08:30.850 --> 01:08:34.000
It's actually a fantastic application,
but it actually highlights

01:08:34.060 --> 01:08:35.620
the problem we want to solve.

01:08:35.640 --> 01:08:38.900
Most people don't have time
to get this stuff right.

01:08:39.180 --> 01:08:41.640
Most people don't know that
they're even getting it wrong,

01:08:41.640 --> 01:08:44.960
because how would you ever know if you
didn't see the two images side by side?

01:08:44.960 --> 01:08:50.880
So we want to come over and
fix this problem in Panther.

01:08:50.880 --> 01:08:52.460
And here's what we've done.

01:08:52.480 --> 01:08:57.330
We've built into Panther some
modifications to the graphic importer

01:08:57.390 --> 01:09:02.060
and exporter routines that basically
allow you to automatically apply the

01:09:02.190 --> 01:09:05.840
profiles kind of behind your back,
so that most applications will

01:09:05.840 --> 01:09:07.850
derive the benefit immediately.

01:09:07.850 --> 01:09:09.160
Can we switch to demo one?

01:09:09.160 --> 01:09:14.080
So I'll open it up in Photoshop again.

01:09:21.100 --> 01:09:22.020
Open it up in dbedit.

01:09:22.100 --> 01:09:29.090
And what you should see this time is
you're getting a very accurate color.

01:09:31.800 --> 01:09:33.800
This is going to be great for consumers.

01:09:33.860 --> 01:09:36.560
The pre-press guys were
already getting things right,

01:09:36.610 --> 01:09:39.550
but consumers are just completely
baffled at what's happening to

01:09:39.620 --> 01:09:42.000
them when they open these images
in different applications and

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:43.160
they get different experience.

01:09:43.190 --> 01:09:44.530
This is going to allow us to solve that.

01:09:44.770 --> 01:09:47.280
Go back to slides, please.

01:09:52.400 --> 01:09:54.380
So that's color
management with QuickTime.

01:09:54.450 --> 01:09:57.410
So the last thing I want to
talk about is QuickTime audio.

01:09:59.120 --> 01:10:02.250
Mac OS X introduced a whole
new audio architecture,

01:10:02.250 --> 01:10:05.180
and this is a major innovation,
not just in the realm of audio,

01:10:05.180 --> 01:10:07.890
but in the realm of operating systems.

01:10:07.990 --> 01:10:10.100
It was a ground-up
redesign of the system.

01:10:10.160 --> 01:10:13.140
We wanted to support all the
modern hardware capabilities,

01:10:13.140 --> 01:10:17.140
and this meant multi-channel,
high data rate, high res,

01:10:17.350 --> 01:10:22.480
greater than 16-bit per sample,
high sample rates.

01:10:25.970 --> 01:10:27.760
just out of range.

01:10:27.760 --> 01:10:28.540
Low latency I/O.

01:10:28.890 --> 01:10:31.750
Anybody working in a professional
audio environment knows that if

01:10:31.850 --> 01:10:35.560
you don't have low latency I/O,
you are not working in a pro domain.

01:10:35.560 --> 01:10:37.410
You can't get your work done.

01:10:37.480 --> 01:10:39.190
It's just unusable.

01:10:39.190 --> 01:10:44.860
Mac OS X has the lowest I/O latency for
audio of any operating system anywhere.

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:49.070
And I would challenge you to put
it up against even a wide range

01:10:49.070 --> 01:10:51.580
of professional audio products.

01:10:51.700 --> 01:10:54.020
It's incredibly compelling.

01:10:54.020 --> 01:10:56.520
As I said, we support bigger, deeper,
wider formats.

01:10:56.520 --> 01:10:58.340
It's got a very flexible plug-in format.

01:10:58.630 --> 01:11:02.910
If you're interested in audio and you'd
like to be able to extend the system,

01:11:02.910 --> 01:11:06.310
there's a great API for doing
that called Audio Unit API,

01:11:06.310 --> 01:11:08.520
and you can learn all
about that at the show.

01:11:08.560 --> 01:11:10.240
And we wanted to deliver
pro-level performance.

01:11:10.250 --> 01:11:12.570
Well, that was core audio.

01:11:12.800 --> 01:11:14.160
What are we going to do in QuickTime?

01:11:14.160 --> 01:11:17.500
It's been a long time since we've
done a fundamental rethinking of

01:11:17.500 --> 01:11:19.630
the QuickTime audio architecture.

01:11:19.630 --> 01:11:21.890
For Panther, we are doing just that.

01:11:22.550 --> 01:11:26.650
It leverages core audio, of course,
and it's available on Macintosh,

01:11:26.720 --> 01:11:27.270
of course.

01:11:27.540 --> 01:11:32.860
Many of these capabilities will
be provided on Windows as well.

01:11:33.090 --> 01:11:35.220
First and foremost,
we break the 64 kilohertz

01:11:35.220 --> 01:11:36.230
sampling rate barrier.

01:11:36.500 --> 01:11:40.340
We support 24-bit,
32-bit floating point formats.

01:11:40.360 --> 01:11:43.190
We support, for the first time,
multi-channel formats.

01:11:43.270 --> 01:11:46.270
And I'm going to show
you some 5.1 audio today,

01:11:46.270 --> 01:11:48.920
but we support all the different formats.

01:11:49.040 --> 01:11:52.240
There's just a zillion of them,
and there's a very flexible architecture

01:11:52.400 --> 01:11:55.980
inside of QuickTime that allows you to
label the tracks appropriately so that

01:11:56.100 --> 01:11:58.040
they end up going to the right speakers.

01:11:58.730 --> 01:12:00.120
And it's very, very powerful.

01:12:00.120 --> 01:12:02.270
We support this both
for uncompressed audio,

01:12:02.270 --> 01:12:05.090
PCM, as well as for compressed
audio formats such as AAC.

01:12:05.200 --> 01:12:08.360
And we've also done a major
rework of the synchronization

01:12:08.440 --> 01:12:12.550
architecture in QuickTime so that
when you have multiple channels,

01:12:12.550 --> 01:12:15.400
you will be guaranteed
sample-accurate synchronization

01:12:15.400 --> 01:12:18.580
across your various tracks,
a promise we do not make today.

01:12:18.580 --> 01:12:20.960
So let me show you how that works.

01:12:21.120 --> 01:12:22.270
